{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520754"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:28:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:28:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13516"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13516"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.46,0.04,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6131"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102414"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6131"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13516"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84888"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11075"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11305"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35806"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42884"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102414"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man is brought to the emergency department with burns sustained in a house fire. He is conscious but in significant pain. His blood pressure is 92/58 mmHg, pulse 118/min, temperature 37.0\u00b0C, respiratory rate 22/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 94% on room air. His body weight is 60 kg. He has superficial burns covering 20% and partial-thickness burns covering 30% of his total body surface area. He is going to be given fluid resuscitation with Lactated Ringer\u0027s solution based on the Parkland Formula.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following would be the most appropriate initial fluid therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["450 mL/hr during the first 8 hours","750 mL/hr during the first 8 hours","450 mL/hr during the first 16 hours.","750 mL/hr during the first 16 hours","400 mL/hr during the first 24 hours"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperficial burns\u003C/strong\u003E are typically not included in fluid resuscitation calculations because they only involve damage to the skin\u0027s outer layer (epidermis) and do not result in significant fluid loss. However, \u003Cstrong\u003Epartial-thickness and full-thickness burns\u003C/strong\u003E, which extend into the deeper layers of the skin (dermis), do contribute to fluid loss and are included in fluid resuscitation calculations. Therefore, in this scenario, only the partial-thickness burns covering 30% of the total body surface area would be counted in the fluid resuscitation calculation. The superficial burns covering 20% of the total body surface area would not be included.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFluid resuscitation is paramount in managing burn injuries to prevent hypovolaemic shock and organ dysfunction. The Parkland formula guides initial fluid therapy, administering 4 mL of lactated Ringer\u0027s solution per kilogram of body weight per percentage of total body surface area burned. Half of the total volume is administered in the first 8 hours, followed by the remaining half over the subsequent 16 hours. This approach aims to restore intravascular volume, optimise tissue perfusion, and mitigate complications like acute kidney injury and compartment syndrome. Monitoring for adequate urine output, vital signs, and clinical response is essential for adjusting fluid therapy. Additionally, attention to electrolyte balance, wound care, and potential complications, such as abdominal compartment syndrome, guides comprehensive burn management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven: Total body surface area (TBSA) burned = 30%\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBody weight = 60 kg\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUsing the Parkland Formula: Total fluid requirement for the first 24 hours\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E= 4 mL/kg/%TBSA \u00d7 body weight \u00d7 %TBSA burned\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E= 4 mL/kg/%TBSA \u00d7 60 kg \u00d7 30 TBSA\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E= 7200 mL in 24 hours\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal volume for the first 8 hours beginning when the patient was\u00a0initially burned\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E= 7200/2 = 3600 mL\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInfusion rate during initial 8 hours = 3600/8 = 450ml/hr\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, the correct hourly rate for administering lactated Ringer\u0027s solution in the initial \u003Cstrong\u003E8 hours is 450 mL/hour\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the superficial and deep burns had been counted together, it would making it 50% TBSA, thereby overestimating the fluid volume (750mL/hr).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe infusion rates of 50% fluid during the initial 16 hours are not incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["When assessing the severity of burns, only partial-thickness and full-thickness burns are taken into account, while superficial burns are not included in the calculation.","The Parkland formula prescribes administering 4 mL of lactated Ringer\u0027s solution per kilogram of body weight per percentage of total body surface area burned, with half of the total volume given over the initial 8 hours and the remainder over the subsequent 16 hours, to be completed within 24 hours."],"references":["Greenhalgh DG, Management of Burns. N Engl J Med 2019; 380:2349-59."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84888"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13516"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84888"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-12T16:06:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T16:07:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6131"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102414"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72"